How Rwanda is preparing its health system for the climate crisis
                    Phaedra Henley1, Thierry Sebakunzi 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0009-0004-8348-08352 & Maria Albin Qambayot1

Nature Health

(2026)Cite this article

Subjects

            Climate-change impactsEducationHealth policy

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

While much of the world still frames climate change as a future environmental or economic challenge, Rwanda is already acting where it matters most: health. In 2024, Rwanda’s Ministry of Health established the ‘Climate Change and Health Technical Working Group’, which brings together experts across sectors to proactively tackle the growing health threats posed by climate change. Sparked by growing concern at the highest levels of health leadership, the ministry convened and coordinated a multisectoral forum to formulate strategies, set research agendas and propose policy recommendations to address both longstanding and emerging climate-related health challenges. To our knowledge, it is the first national-level health sector initiative of its kind. And it could not have come at a more urgent time.Climate change is already reshaping the health landscape across Africa and beyond. Rising temperatures, extreme weather events and shifting ecosystems are driving up the incidence of vector-borne diseases such as malaria, disrupting food security, displacing communities, and placing increased strain on fragile health systems1,2. For example, Cyclone Freddy (a devastating storm that hit Malawi) was accompanied by widespread population displacements, a cholera outbreak and an increased spread of malaria, which placed the already-weak health system under an immense burden3. These are not distant projections; they are current realities. Yet in many countries, climate change is still treated as a separate issue from health, siloed under ministries of environment or infrastructure, and far removed from those tasked with protecting public health.



